PR’s Stats Report!

Following our Stats Plan…

Loading Files

Here’s our dataset.

library(tidyverse)
library(janitor)
library(lubridate)
library(skimr)
library(lme4)
library(jtools)
library(Hmisc)
# Question Data
question_key <- read_csv("InferentialStatusKey copy.csv") %>%
  clean_names() %>%
  mutate(question_number = tolower(question_number),
         literal_status = tolower(literal_status)) %>%
  separate(question_number, into = c("left","right")) %>%
  unite(col = "question_number", left, right, sep = "_") %>%
  select(question_number, literal_status) # drop all other columns for now
# Full Data
fulldata <- read_csv("CMP4_FullData_9.25.18.csv") %>%
  clean_names() %>%
  select(-(answer1:answer15)) %>% # remove answers
  filter(age_at_test <= 18) %>% # 18 or below 
  filter(age_at_test > 7) %>% # 8 or older 
  filter(school != "HSDB") %>% # No HSDB
  mutate(assessment_date = dmy(assessment_date)) %>%
  group_by(student_id) %>%
  arrange(assessment_date) %>%
  slice(1) %>% # Keep earliest assessment date, throw away all later assessments
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate_at(vars(parents, ethnicity, student_id, school), as.factor)
# Calculate IC and LC scores 
ic_lc_scores_cleaned <- fulldata %>%
  select(student_id, answ_rw1:answ_rw15) %>%
  select(-c(answ_rw6, answ_rw7, answ_rw10)) %>%
  gather(key = "question_number", value = "answer", answ_rw1:answ_rw15) 
ic_lc_scores <- ic_lc_scores_cleaned %>%
  left_join(question_key, by = "question_number") %>%
  group_by(student_id, literal_status) %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(answer, na.rm = T)) %>%
  spread(literal_status, mean)
task_percents <- ic_lc_scores_cleaned %>%
  group_by(student_id) %>%
  summarise(task_percent = mean(answer, na.rm = T))
# Add IC and LC scores back into fulldata
fulldata <- fulldata %>% 
  select(-task_percent) %>%
  left_join(ic_lc_scores, by = "student_id") %>%
  left_join(task_percents, by = "student_id")
fulldata

Checking for Vocabulary Correlations

Let’s check if ant4 and syn4 are correlated or not. If they’re correlated, we want to group them in a new composite. If they’re not, treat them as separate predictors.

vocab_corr <- cor.test(fulldata$ant4, fulldata$syn4, use = "complete.obs")

So ant4 and syn4 are very correlated, with r = 0.76688 and p = 0. So we’ll make a new composite vocab by averaging together ant4 and syn4. If one of the test scores is missing from a student’s data, we’ll use the other one in its place. Here’s some examples of our new vocab composite score.

# Calculate composites
composites <- fulldata %>%
  select(student_id, syn4, ant4) %>%
  group_by(student_id) %>%
  gather(key = "test", value = "score", syn4, ant4) %>%
  group_by(student_id) %>%
  summarise(vocab = mean(score, na.rm = T))
# Join back to fulldata
fulldata <- fulldata %>%
  left_join(composites, by = "student_id")
# See composites
fulldata %>%
  select(student_id, syn4, ant4, vocab) %>%
  head(20)

HiReAn: Literal ASL

Before we start the hierarchical regressions, I’m going to reduce the dataset to only the variables we’re looking at, and then drop any rows that are missing any of the variables we are using here. Doing so, 60 rows were dropped. Let’s see those we dropped, below. Almost of them were dropped because they didn’t take the ant4 and syn4 tests, that’s why.

testdata <- fulldata %>%
  select(age_at_test, parents, vocab, vocda2, stxd4, literal, inferential, task_percent) %>%
  drop_na
anti_join(fulldata, testdata) %>%
  select(age_at_test, parents, ant4, syn4, vocab, vocda2, stxd4, literal, inferential, task_percent)
Joining, by = c("age_at_test", "parents", "stxd4", "vocda2", "inferential", "literal", "task_percent", "vocab")

Now the models, with outcome being Literal ASL.

lc_fit1 <- lm(data = testdata, literal ~ age_at_test)
lc_fit2 <- lm(data = testdata, literal ~ age_at_test + parents)
lc_fit3 <- lm(data = testdata, literal ~ age_at_test + parents + vocab + vocda2)
lc_fit4 <- lm(data = testdata, literal ~ age_at_test + parents + vocab + vocda2 + stxd4)
anova(lc_fit1, lc_fit2, lc_fit3, lc_fit4)

HiReAn: Task Performance (ASL Comprehension)

Now the models for task performance.

If you want to know the relationship between literal and the final score, and inferential and the final score, use the correlation table above. From there we can see that literal has a slightly stronger effect on task performance than inferential, but again, all 3 are nearly perfectly correlated (the r-value is really close to 1) that they all can be argued to be “measuring the same thing.”

asl_fit1 <- lm(data = testdata, task_percent ~ age_at_test)
asl_fit2 <- lm(data = testdata, task_percent ~ age_at_test + parents)
asl_fit3 <- lm(data = testdata, task_percent ~ age_at_test + parents + vocab + vocda2)
asl_fit4 <- lm(data = testdata, task_percent ~ age_at_test + parents + vocab + vocda2 + stxd4)
anova(asl_fit1, asl_fit2, asl_fit3, asl_fit4)

TLC Testing

TLC took the test twice. Let’s compare their scores.

tlcdata <- read_csv("CMP4_FullData_9.25.18.csv") %>%
  clean_names() %>%
  filter(school == "TLC") %>%
  mutate(time = case_when(
    assessment_date == '02/11/2015' ~ "time1",
    TRUE ~ "time2"
  )) %>%
  select(-(answer1:answer15)) %>% # remove answers
  filter(age_at_test <= 18) %>% # 18 or below 
  filter(age_at_test > 7) %>% # 8 or older 
  mutate_at(vars(parents, ethnicity, student_id, school), as.factor)
# Calculate IC and LC scores 
ic_lc_scores_cleaned <- tlcdata %>%
  select(student_id, time, answ_rw1:answ_rw15) %>%
  select(-c(answ_rw6, answ_rw7, answ_rw10)) %>%
  gather(key = "question_number", value = "answer", answ_rw1:answ_rw15) 
ic_lc_scores <- ic_lc_scores_cleaned %>%
  left_join(question_key, by = "question_number") %>%
  group_by(student_id, time, literal_status) %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(answer, na.rm = T)) %>%
  spread(literal_status, mean)
task_percents <- ic_lc_scores_cleaned %>%
  group_by(student_id, time) %>%
  summarise(task_percent = mean(answer, na.rm = T))
# Add IC and LC scores back into fulldata
tlcdata <- tlcdata %>% 
  select(-task_percent) %>%
  left_join(ic_lc_scores, by = c("student_id", "time")) %>%
  left_join(task_percents, by = c("student_id", "time"))
tlcdata

Linear Modeling, STEPWISE MODEL SELECTION

But really what you are doing is stepwise model selection. See explanation here.. You want to find the most parsiminous model that best explains the data. AIC is an arbitrary measure of the “quality” of a model, and the smaller (or more negative) the AIC is, the better. So by using step() R will do all the work for you of taking out one variable, then another variable, and so on.

Literal

So running step(m_lc) returns the “best” model to be literal ~ age_at_test + stxd4 + vocab_composite. Basically: deaf/hearing contributed nothing to the model so they took it out. But age_at_test was still important so it was left in there.

final_m_lc <- step(m_lc)

Visualizations!

  1. Participants: I was thinking of a nice histogram of participants where x is age and y is number of participants…. for each age there are two bar graphs merged to show difference… ie if 8 children have hearing parents and 4 have deaf parents then the top part of the graph should indicate hearing parents whereas the bottom part show deaf parent.
completedata %>%
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = age_at_test, fill = parents) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(7,18)) +
  theme_linedraw() +
  labs(x = "age",
       y = "participants",
       title = "Age of Participants")

completedata %>%
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = as.factor(age_at_test), fill = parents) +
  geom_bar(data = filter(completedata, parents == "DP")) + 
  geom_bar(data = filter(completedata, parents == "HP"), 
           mapping = aes(y = - ..count.. ),
           position = "identity") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = abs, limits = c(-25, 25)) +
  labs(x = "age",
       y = "participants",
       title = "Age of Participants") +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_linedraw()
